1 SECTION 1.(c) G.S. 108A-115 reads as rewritten:
2 "§ 108A-115. Duty to report suspected fraud; content of report; immunity for reporting.
3 (a) Any financial institution, or officer or employee thereof, having reasonable cause to
4 believe that a disabled adult or older adult is the victim or target of financial exploitation shall
5 report such this information to the following:
6 (1) Persons on the list provided by the customer under G.S. 108A-114, if such a
7 list has been provided by the customer. provided. The financial institution may
8 choose not to contact persons on the provided list if the financial institution
9 suspects that those persons are financially exploiting the disabled adult or
10 older adult.
11 (2) The appropriate local law enforcement agency.
12 (3) The appropriate county department of social services, if the customer is a
13 disabled adult.
14 (b) The report may be made orally or in writing. The report shall include the name and
15 address of the disabled adult or older adult, the nature of the suspected financial exploitation, and
16 any other pertinent information.
17 (c) No financial institution, or officer or employee thereof, who officer, employee, or
18 agent, that acts in good faith in making a report under this section may be held liable in any action
19 for doing so. Furthermore, a financial institution, and its officers, employees, and agents, shall
20 not be compelled in any action to identify the existence of or the contents of a suspicious activity
21 report related to suspected financial abuse activity that may have been filed with the U.S.
22 Department of the Treasury's Financial Crimes Enforcement Network pursuant to requirements
23 of the Bank Secrecy Act, 31 U.S.C. § 5318(g)(2), and its implementing regulations."
24 SECTION 1.(d) Article 6A of Chapter 108A of the General Statutes is amended by
25 adding two new sections to read:
26 "§ 108A-118. Transaction delays and refusals.
27 (a) A financial institution may choose to delay or refuse a disbursement or transaction
28 from an account of a disabled adult or older adult or an account for which a disabled adult or
29 older adult is a beneficiary or beneficial owner if all of the following apply:
30 (1) The financial institution and its employees believe that financial exploitation
31 of the older adult or disabled adult may have occurred, may have been
32 attempted, or is occurring or is being attempted.
33 (2) The belief is based on individual observation or information received,
34 including information received from a government agency or law enforcement
35 agency.
36 (3) The financial institution promptly initiates an internal review of the facts and
37 circumstances that caused an employee of the financial institution to delay or
38 refuse the disbursement or transaction.
39 (b) If the conditions of subsection (a) of this section are met, a financial institution may
40 do any of the following:
41 (1) Delay or refuse one or more transactions with or involving the older adult or
42 disabled adult.
43 (2) Delay or refuse to permit the withdrawal or disbursement of funds contained
44 in the older adult or disabled adult's account.
45 (3) Prevent a change in ownership of the older adult or disabled adult's account.
46 (4) Prevent a transfer of funds from the older adult or disabled adult's account to
47 an account owned wholly or partially by another person.
48 (5) Refuse to comply with instructions given by an agent or a person acting for or
49 with an agent under a power of attorney signed or purported to have been
50 signed by the older adult or disabled adult.
House Bill 754-First Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (6) Prevent the designation or change the designation of beneficiaries to receive
2 any property, benefit, or contract rights for an older adult or disabled adult at
3 death.
4 (c) A financial institution shall use discretion to determine whether or not to act under
5 subsections (a) and (b) of this section based on the information available to its staff at the time.
6 The authority to delay a transaction expires upon the earlier of the following:
7 (1) Thirty business days after the date on which the depository institution first
8 acted under the authority in this section.
9 (2) When the depository institution is satisfied in its discretion that the transaction
10 or act will not likely result in financial exploitation of the older adult or
11 disabled adult.
12 (3) Upon an order of a court directing the release of funds.
13 (d) Unless otherwise directed by order of a court, a financial institution may extend the
14 duration of a delay up to an additional 30 days based on a reasonable belief that the financial
15 exploitation of an older adult or disabled adult may continue to occur or continues to be
16 attempted.
17 (e) A financial institution shall create and maintain for at least five years from the date
18 of the delayed or refused disbursement or transaction a written or electronic record that includes,
19 at a minimum, the following information:
20 (1) The date on which the delay or refusal was first placed.
21 (2) The name and address of the older adult or disabled adult.
22 (3) The business location of the financial institution.
23 (4) The name and title of the employee who reported suspected financial
24 exploitation of the older adult or disabled adult pursuant to G.S. 108A-115.
25 (5) The facts and circumstances that caused the employee to report suspected
26 financial exploitation.
27 (f) A financial institution that acts in good faith and exercises reasonable care to comply
28 with this section is immune from any civil, criminal, or administrative liability that might
29 otherwise arise from the financial institution's action, inaction, or delay in a disbursement or
30 transaction in accordance with this section. This protection from liability also extends to
31 employees of a financial institution. This subsection does not supersede or diminish any
32 immunity granted elsewhere in this Chapter. If a financial institution or its employees make, or
33 choose not to make, a disclosure to a trusted contact or participate in a judicial proceeding,
34 administrative proceeding, or investigation arising from a notification or report, the financial
35 institution and its employees are immune from any civil, criminal, or administrative liability
36 arising from the disclosure, nondisclosure, notification, or participation, unless the financial
37 institution or its employees had actual knowledge of financial exploitation and acted with a
38 malicious purpose. For purposes of this section, a financial institution and its employees are
39 deemed to be acting with reasonable care if the financial institution has established training
40 policies, programs, and procedures for its employees consistent with the requirements of
41 subsection (g) of this section.
42 (g) Before placing a delay on a disbursement or transaction pursuant to this section, a
43 financial institution shall do all of the following:
44 (1) Develop training policies or programs reasonably designed to educate
45 employees who perform or approve transactions on behalf of customers on
46 issues pertaining to financial exploitation of older adults or disabled adults.
47 (2) With respect to an individual who begins employment with a financial
48 institution, the training shall be conducted within one year after the date on
49 which the individual becomes employed by or affiliated or associated with the
50 financial institution.
