1 (3) Develop, maintain, and enforce written procedures regarding the manner in
2 which suspected financial exploitation is reviewed internally, including, if
3 applicable, the manner in which suspected financial exploitation is required to
4 be reported to supervisory personnel.
5 (h) Absent a reasonable belief of financial exploitation as provided in this section, this
6 section does not otherwise alter a financial institution's obligations to all parties authorized to
7 transact business on an account and any trusted contact named on the account. This section does
8 not create new rights for or impose new obligations or new duties on a financial institution under
9 other applicable law.
10 (i) Notwithstanding any other law to the contrary, the following provisions apply:
11 (1) The refusal to engage in a transaction as authorized under this section does
12 not constitute the wrongful dishonor of an item under G.S. 25-4-402.
13 (2) A reasonable belief that payment of a check will facilitate the financial
14 exploitation of an older adult or disabled adult constitutes reasonable grounds
15 to doubt the collectability of the item for purposes of the federal Check
16 Clearing for the 21st Century Act, 12 U.S.C. § 5001 et seq., the federal
17 Expedited Funds Availability Act, 12 U.S.C. § 4001 et seq., and 12 C.F.R.
18 Part 229. Nothing in this subdivision, however, requires financial institutions
19 and their employees to review the checks of older adults or disabled adults.
20 (j) A delay or refusal to complete a funds transfer request as authorized under this section
21 does not violate Article 4A of Chapter 25 of the General Statutes. Furthermore, if a transaction
22 is delayed under this section, the payment order is not deemed as received until the hold is
23 removed and the financial institution submits the payment order for processing. "Funds transfer"
24 and "payment order" have the meaning provided in Article 4A of Chapter 25 of the General
25 Statutes.
26 "§ 108A-119. Notifications to trusted contacts.
27 (a) A financial institution may notify a trusted contact, if any, if the financial institution
28 or its employees believe that financial exploitation of an older adult or disabled adult is occurring,
29 has or may have occurred, is being attempted, or has been or may have been attempted.
30 (b) A financial institution and its employees may choose not to notify a trusted contact if
31 the financial institution or its employees believe that the third party is, may be, or may have been
32 engaged in the financial exploitation of an older adult or disabled adult.
33 (c) When providing information, a financial institution or its employees may limit the
34 information provided to disclosing their suspicion that the older adult or disabled adult may be a
35 victim or target of financial exploitation.
36 (d) Any disclosure under this section is exempt from State privacy laws."
